'''Court sanction''' is an order granted by a [[court]] as per an appeal that allows a specific action or prevents any other actions to restrict a specific action from happening. Commonly, this specific action might be deemed against law otherwise (without obtaining a court sanction).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=GdUa8VqNb80C&pg=PA153&dq=%22court+sanction%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiF-vCB373eAhWr0FQKHWURBwAQ6AEIMDAB|title=Casenote Legal Briefs for Civil Procedure, Keyed to Field, Kaplan and Clermont|first=Casenote Legal|last=Briefs|date=1 August 2010|publisher=Aspen Publishers Online|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=afCtbymBwLIC&pg=PA124&dq=%22court+sanction%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiF-vCB373eAhWr0FQKHWURBwAQ6AEINjAC|title=Legal Analysis and Communication|first=M. H. Sam|last=Jacobson|date=5 November 2018|publisher=AuthorHouse|via=Google Books}}</ref> In some countries, a court sanction cannot be withheld by any other court even a court superior to that court.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=0AUSAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1369&dq=%22court+sanction%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiF-vCB373eAhWr0FQKHWURBwAQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=%22court+sanction%22&f=false|title=Digest of Indian Law Reports and Law Reports Indian Appeals: To December 1883|first=Reginald M. A.|last=Branson|date=5 November 1884|publisher=|via=Google Books}}</ref>

