{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = The Origins of the Urban Crisis: Race and Inequality in Postwar Detroit | title_orig = | translator = | image = Urban crisis.gif | caption = | author = Thomas J. Sugrue | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | subject = [[Sociology]], [[Urban planning]], [[History]] | language = English | genre = nonfiction | publisher = [[Princeton University Press]] | release_date = April 1996 | pages = 375 pp | isbn = 0-691-12186-9 | dewey= 305.8/00977434 22 | congress= F574.D49 N4835 2005 | oclc= 59879791 }}
'''''The Origins of the Urban Crisis: Race and Inequality in Postwar Detroit''''', is the first book by historian and Detroit native [[Thomas J. Sugrue]] in which he examines the role race, housing, job discrimination, and capital flight played in the [[decline of Detroit]]. Sugrue argues that the decline of Detroit began long before the [[1967 Detroit riot|1967 race riot]]. Sugrue argues that institutionalized and often legalized racism resulted in sharply limited opportunities for Detroit blacks for most of the twentieth century. He also argues that the process of deindustrialization, the flight of investment and jobs from the city, began in the 1950s as employers moved to suburban areas and small towns and also introduced new labor saving technologies. The book has won multiple awards including a [[Bancroft Prize]] in 1998.<ref name="Bancroft">{{cite web|url=http://library.columbia.edu/eguides/amerihist/bancroft/previous_awards.html|title=The Bancroft Prizes: Previous Awards|work=Columbia University Libraries|accessdate=18 July 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130410205503/http://library.columbia.edu/eguides/amerihist/bancroft/previous_awards.html|archivedate=10 April 2013|df=}}</ref>
==Awards== ''Origins of the Urban Crisis'' won the 1998 [[Bancroft Prize]] in American History,<ref name="Bancroft" /> the 1996 Social Science History Association President's Book Award<ref name="JMMH">{{cite journal|year=1999|title=HISTORICALLY SPEAKING: An Interview with Thomas J. Sugrue|journal=The Journal for MultiMedia History|publisher=University at Albany|volume=2|url=http://www.albany.edu/jmmh/vol2no1/sugrue.html|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> for a first work by a beginning scholar,<ref name="SSHA">{{cite web|url=http://www.ssha.org/awards|title=Awards|publisher=Social Science History Association|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> the 1996 [[Philip Taft]] Prize in Labor History,<ref name="Taft">{{cite web|url=http://www.ilr.cornell.edu/taftaward/awardRecipients/pastRecipients.html|title=Past Taft Awards Recipients|publisher=Cornell University ILR School|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> and the 1997 Urban History Association Prize for Best Book in North American Labor History.<ref name="UHA">{{cite web|url=http://uha.udayton.edu/winners.html|title=The Urban History Association Past Prize Winners|accessdate=18 July 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121210111800/http://uha.udayton.edu/winners.html|archivedate=10 December 2012|df=}}</ref> In 2005, Princeton University Press selected ''Origins of the Urban Crisis'' as one of its 100 most influential books of the preceding century and issued it as a Princeton Classic. In 2014, Princeton published a new edition of the book, with a new preface discussing Detroit's bankruptcy.
